docs.lead_paragraph: CLEVELAND — President Trump kept China in his sights on Saturday, using a visit to the industrial Midwest to promote his hard-line trade tactics, while the White House rebuked the Chinese government for demanding that foreign airlines change how they refer to Taiwan.

headline.main: In Discussion Ostensibly About Tax Cuts, Trump Keeps China in Cross Hairs
headline.print_headline: In Tax-Cut Round Table, Trump Detours to Talk Up His Popularity

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The White House on Wednesday brushed aside threats by North Korea to cancel a summit meeting between President Trump and its leader, Kim Jong-un, but the harsh words underscored the chasm that will separate the two leaders next month in Singapore over how to deal with North Korea’s nuclear arsenal.

headline.main: North Korean Threats Are ‘Splash of Cold Water’ on Expectations for Talks
headline.print_headline: Threats Add a Wobble  To a High-Wire Act  Of Nuclear Negotiation

docs.abstract: Justice Anthony M. Kennedy occupied a place at the court’s ideological center for his entire tenure, with his vote often the crucial one in closely divided cases.
docs.snippet: Justice Anthony M. Kennedy occupied a place at the court’s ideological center for his entire tenure, with his vote often the crucial one in closely divided cases.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Justice Anthony M. Kennedy has served for more than 30 years under two chief justices: William H. Rehnquist and John G. Roberts Jr. Courts are by tradition named for the chief justice. Since 2005, it has been the Roberts court.

headline.main: In Influence if Not in Title, This Has Been the Kennedy Court
headline.print_headline: This Was the Kennedy Court, In His Influence if Not in Title

docs.abstract: Educators fear that the changes, which the Trump administration devised to curb intellectual property theft, will hinder innovation, intensify anti-Chinese aggressions and deter talented applicants.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump’s confrontation with China is beginning to ripple through American academic and research institutions, as a crackdown on visas for certain Chinese citizens has left the higher education community wondering how it will adapt to the administration’s effort to stop intellectual property theft and slow China’s push for technological supremacy.

headline.main: Visa Restrictions for Chinese Students Alarm Academia
headline.print_headline: Trade War With China Trickles Into Academia, With Tinges of Racism
